player.seasonOutlook: Jones signed with Jacksonville after spending his first five NFL seasons with Buffalo and Las Vegas. The 2017 second-round pick didn't work out with the Bills and was a backup for most of his first 2 1/2 seasons with the Raiders, but he emerged as one of Derek Carr's top targets after last season's Week 8 bye. From that point on, Jones averaged 6.3 targets per game while working primarily as a vertical threat (11th-highest average depth of target). The usage didn't allow much production (43.1 yards per game and zero TDs) and Jones remains without a top-30 fantasy campaign for his career. The 27-year-old will compete for a starting gig in Jacksonville, but he's a long shot for a big enough role to allow consistent fantasy production. He belongs on waivers.

Eskridge was selected in the second round of the 2021 draft, but his rookie campaign was derailed by a concussion suffered in Week 1. He handled three touches on his first 11 NFL snaps, but settled into a situational role once he returned to action in Week 10. He was limited to an ugly 64 yards on 20 targets (3.2 YPT), but showed his playmaking ability with 59 yards on four carries. Eskridge is old for a second-year player (25) and the entire offense took a hit when the team traded Russell Wilson. Especially with DK Metcalf, Tyler Lockett and Noah Fant ahead of him for targets, Eskridge is a long shot for consistent fantasy value. He's best viewed as a dynasty stash.

An underrated aspect of Bill Belichick's legacy is his ability to get the most out of what often seems like an average defense on paper. New England's D/ST has finished as a top-12 fantasy unit nine times over the last 10 seasons. That includes a third-place finish in 2021 that was powered by 10 top-10 weeks (second most). New England has at least 18 INTs in four consecutive seasons (only four other teams have done this over the last 20 years) and has finished no worse than 10th in points allowed since 2012. New England's defense again looks "just OK" on paper (star CB J.C. Jackson is obviously a huge loss), but history shows Belichick is a good bet to keep this unit near the top. Consider it a fringe starting option.

The Texans took a flier on Jordan in the fifth round of last year's draft and the Miami product appeared in nine games during his rookie campaign. It didn't take Jordan long to find his way to a situational role and he ended up handling a 10% target share (3.3 per game) and contributing four top-12 fantasy outings. A playmaker with the ball in his hands, Jordan led the 2021 rookie TE class with an 8.2 RAC during his final three collegiate seasons. He is still very young (entering his age-22 season) and Houston's offense isn't likely to be particularly good, but he's a sleeper worth monitoring. Consider Jordan with a late pick in deeper leagues.

Conklin signed with the Jets after a breakout 2021 campaign in which he was on the field for 81% of Minnesota's offensive snaps. He stepped in for an injured Irv Smith Jr. and ranked no lower than 12th at the position in snaps, routes, targets, receptions and end zone targets (eight). Conklin has primarily been a short-range target (5.6 aDOT) and is a strong bet for a much-lesser role with C.J. Uzomah and Jeremy Ruckert also on the new-look Jets' TE depth chart. Last season marked Conklin's lone top-40 fantasy campaign and he has four touchdowns on 129 career targets. He's not a fantasy option.

Likely was selected by the Ravens in the fourth round of April's draft. He is one of the most accomplished pass catchers in this rookie class and that was highlighted by a 59-912-12 receiving line in 2021. He handled a hefty 25% target share, paced this TE class with a 3.4 YPRR and posted a 11.5 YPT (third best). Likely scored at least five TDs in all four seasons at Coastal Carolina while running nearly half of his routes from the slot. He is a bit undersized and may not emerge as an impact blocker, but he's a decent athlete (class-best 36-inch vertical at the combine) with good speed and receiving skills. There's long-term upside here, but Likely has no short-term fantasy appeal with Mark Andrews locked in atop the depth chart.

Peoples-Jones entered the 2021 season ticketed for a situational role, but injuries and the Odell Beckham Jr. trade led to the 2020 sixth-round pick playing 78% of the snaps during 14 active weeks. The hefty playing time didn't lead to much fantasy production, though. Peoples-Jones primarily operated as a vertical target (his 15.5 average depth of target was second highest in the league), which helped him to 10.3 yards per target (sixth highest), but didn't allow much volume (4.1 targets per game). He had two weekly fantasy finishes better than 35th. The arrival of Deshaun Watson helps Peoples-Jones' stock, but first he'll need to fend of Anthony Schwartz and rookie David Bell for regular snaps behind Amari Cooper. The 23-year-old is best as a late-round flier in deep leagues.

Berrios re-signed with the Jets and the 2018 sixth-round pick will again play a situational slot role. He has played at least 40% of the offensive snaps in 11 games in his career (all with the Jets). During those 11 outings, he averaged a hefty 26% target share (7.7 per game) and 12.6 fantasy PPG (would've ranked 33rd in 2021). Six of the 11 outings came in 2021 and Berrios was the No. 22 fantasy WR during those weeks. The bad news is that Berrios is stuck behind Elijah Moore, first-round rookie Garrett Wilson and Corey Davis on the depth chart. If one misses time, perhaps Berrios can sneak back onto the PPR sleeper radar, but the 26-year-old has a very limited ceiling. He can be left on waivers.

Jones signed with the Chiefs after four unceremonious fantasy seasons in Tampa Bay. The 2018 second-round pick peaked with a pair of top-25 fantasy campaigns in 2019 and 2020, but he took a back seat to Leonard Fournette last season and was limited to 111 touches. Despite falling out of favor in Tampa Bay, there is hope for Jones, as he's shown to be an effective rusher and is still pretty young (25). Also, he's joining an elite offense that doesn't have a proven long-term answer at running back. Clyde Edwards-Helaire is the favorite for lead-back duties, but his inconsistent production and durability woes present Jones an opportunity for substantial work. He's well worth a late-round flier.

Mayfield was traded to Carolina and will take over as the team's starting QB after spending his first four NFL seasons in Cleveland. The 2018 first-overall pick has flashed at times (especially late in the 2020 season), but inconsistent play and a lack of rushing contributions (571 yards and 5 TDs in 60 games) has left him without a single top-15 fantasy campaign. Mayfield is aggressive (career 8.8 average depth of throw) and a potential breakout 2021 season was derailed by injury, so a sliver of hope remains for the 27-year-old. Mayfield's offensive line won't be as good in Carolina, but he does have a good group of targets led by DJ Moore, Christian McCaffrey and Robbie Anderson. Mayfield is only worth drafting late in superflex leagues.

Watson was traded to Cleveland after sitting out the entire 2021 season. Prior to the lost year, Watson finished as a top-five fantasy QB in three straight seasons and it could have been four if not for a torn ACL as a rookie in 2017. The dual-threat playmaker ranked no lower than sixth among QBs in rushing yards in each of his last three seasons, while adding 15 TDs with his legs along the way. Watson's passing ability showed continual improvement, as he paced the NFL in passing yards (4,823) and YPA (8.9), while posting 33 TDs and just 7 INTs in 2020. Amari Cooper aside, Watson doesn't have a standout group of targets in Cleveland, but the offensive line is outstanding and his rushing prowess supplies him with elite fantasy upside. Watson will be suspended for the first 11 games of the season, so he's only worth stashing in deep superflex leagues.

Mills returns as the starter in Houston. The 2021 third-round pick played relatively well in 13 appearances as a rookie despite some rough conditions in Houston. He tossed 16 TDs to 10 INTs and completed a healthy 67% of his passes. He hit for the occasional big fantasy week (four top-10s), but generally wasn't a viable option (28th in PPG during 11 weeks he played in full). Mills is a nonfactor with his legs, and the supporting cast in Houston remains a work in progress behind Brandin Cooks. He's not on the fantasy radar.

Mariota is competing with third-round rookie Desmond Ridder to replace Matt Ryan as the Falcons' starting QB. Mariota has barely seen the field since losing the starting gig in Tennessee in 2019. He's played extended snaps in one game over the last two seasons and showed well in that 2020 Week 15 outing (226 passing yards, 88 rushing yards and a pair of TDs). Of course, prior to that, the 2015 second-overall pick struggled during five seasons in Tennessee. Mariota has been effective with his legs throughout his career (264-1,574-13 rushing line), but that has yet to translate to a top-12 fantasy campaign (he's finished better than 18th once). We shouldn't expect that to change in Atlanta's rebuilding offense. He's not a good QB2 option.

After spending four years as Pitt's starting quarterback, Pickett was selected by the Steelers with the 20th pick of April's draft. Pickett enjoyed a breakout 2021 campaign, totaling 47 TDs and 4,319 pass yards. His 81.2 QBR was best in this rookie class and his 1.4% INT rate was second best. He's primarily a pocket passer, but he's a good athlete and was one of four QBs in this class to scramble for over 400 yards last season. Small hands (8.5") and age (easily oldest among the top QB prospects) are knocks, but that's more than offset by his strong passing efficiency. Pickett will compete with Mitchell Trubisky and Mason Rudolph to replace Ben Roethlisberger as the Steelers' starting QB and the history of first-round QBs suggests he'll be under center full time by mid-season. He's only worth drafting in superflex and dynasty leagues.

Watkins signed with the Packers after one unsuccessful season in Baltimore, as he was limited to career-low marks in receptions, receiving yards and touchdowns. Watkins missed four games and has now been sidelined for multiple games in six of his last seven seasons. He hasn't produced a top-40 fantasy campaign since 2015 and he's never finished better than 20th. On paper, the 29-year-old is in a good spot with Aaron Rodgers under center and with the likes of Allen Lazard, Randall Cobb and a pair of rookies as his chief competition for snaps and targets. However, he's been here before many times and hasn't come through. Watkins may flash with the occasional big game, but he's barely worth considering late in your draft.

Agholor is back for his second season with the Patriots after an underwhelming showing in 2021. The 2015 first-round pick was on the field often (81% of pass plays when active), but was limited to 4.3 targets per game -- his lowest since his rookie season. Agholor was utilized primarily as a deep threat (top five in average depth of target for the second straight season), but he and Mac Jones simply didn't connect very often. Agholor finished 75th in fantasy PPG and hasn't had a top-30 campaign since finishing a career-best 23rd in 2017. With DeVante Parker and second-round rookie Tyquan Thornton added to the fold, Agholor will be limited to situational duties and is well off the fantasy radar.

Conner was selected by the Jaguars in the fifth round of April's draft. Conner is a big, tough back who handled limited touches during three seasons (35 games) at Ole Miss. Conner's efficiency is unimpressive, as his YAC and forced missed tackle profile was weak during his career and especially poor in 2021. He was limited to 35 collegiate targets, so it's unknown if he'll contribute in the passing game in the pros. He could find his way to some early-career work behind Travis Etienne as James Robinson recovering from a torn Achilles, but is only worth rostering in dynasty for now.

Moss is entering his third NFL season having yet to emerge as a consistent producer since being selected in the third round of the 2020 draft. Moss has flashed at times, but he's missed action due to injury both seasons and, after briefly sharing the role, lost out to Devin Singletary for lead back duties last season. In Moss' defense, he didn't get much pre-contact help last season (1.5 YBC) and showed well after contact (2.1 YAC) and in the passing game (6.2 YPT). Still, he's yet to post a top-45 fantasy campaign and is behind Singletary, rookie James Cook and perhaps Duke Johnson on the depth chart. Moss is only 24, but he's well off the fantasy radar at the moment.

Bernard re-signed with Tampa Bay and will compete with Ke'Shawn Vaughn and rookie Rachaad White for change-of-pace work behind feature back Leonard Fournette. Bernard was expected to play a significant passing-game role last season, but instead was limited to 28 targets to go along with eight carries. Bernard is now 30 years old and could be as low as fourth in the RB pecking order. Even if Fournette misses time, White is a standout pass-catching prospect and would almost certainly play a big role in that area. Bernard is not on the fantasy radar.

Reynolds barely saw the field during his first two NFL seasons after going undrafted back in 2019. Things changed in Detroit last season when D'Andre Swift and Jamaal Williams were out with injuries. Reynolds came out of nowhere to produce 99 yards on 13 touches in his season debut in Week 14 and followed with 117 yards on 27 touches in Week 15. Reynolds was limited to a situational role the rest of the way, but the Kutztown University product impressed enough that he's in good shape for a spot on the 53-man roster this season. He's not worth drafting, but is worth monitoring in the event of a Swift or Williams injury.

The Rams may have won the Super Bowl last season, but their D/ST fell to 17th in fantasy points after four consecutive top-10 campaigns. Los Angeles dipped to mid-pack in yards and points allowed after allowing the fewest in both in 2020. On the plus side, the Rams finished third in both INTs and sacks. The unit still includes star power in the form of elite playmakers Jalen Ramsey, Aaron Donald and newcomer Bobby Wagner, though some juice was lost when Von Miller and Darious Williams signed elsewhere. This is a top-heavy unit, but it has enough firepower to flirt with consistent fantasy success and is worth consideration with one of your final picks.

The 10th-place finish by the Titans' D/ST in 2021 was its third top 12 over the last four seasons. Tennessee has finished no lower than 10th in INTs each of the last three seasons and was top 12 in sacks, yards allowed, points allowed and touchdowns last season. Tennessee's success was fueled by the likes of Jeffery Simmons, Harold Landry III, Denico Autry, Kevin Byard and Amani Hooker, all of whom are back for 2022. The unit will also have a healthy Bud Dupree and Caleb Farley after both missed extended action last season. Tennessee didn't make any major offseason veteran additions, but keeping its core of stars in place sets the Titans up with a solid defense and suggests they'll remain a viable streaming option again in 2022.

Carolina selected Tremble in the third round of the 2021 draft and the team was so impressed by his progression that it traded starting TE Dan Arnold after Week 3. Tremble's playing time increased from Week 4 on, but his average of 2.7 targets per game led to a weak 19-150-1 receiving line and placed him 46th at the position in fantasy points. Tremble was utilized down field (8.4 aDOT was eighth highest), but struggled with efficiency, ranking among the bottom-three tight ends in catch rate, drop rate and yards per target. Tremble remains Carolina's top receiving TE and, with Baker Mayfield under center, is a candidate for a leap forward in his second season. He's worth a look in two-TE formats.

Smith signed a four-year, $50 million contract with New England last offseason, but the hefty payday didn't translate to much production. Smith handled at least five targets in each of the first four games, but was then demoted to 7.1 routes and 2.0 targets per game the rest of the season. Smith is strictly a short-area target (career 5.6 aDOT) who does a nice job with the ball in his hands (his career 7.3 RAC is second best at TE since he was drafted), but aside of an outlier 2020 season in which he caught eight TDs, he simply hasn't been a factor near the goal line (nine TDs in his other four NFL seasons). Hunter Henry is the top TE in New England and, even if Smith plays more this season, consistent fantasy production from the 27-year-old is a long shot.

Hill has converted to tight end and will compete with the likes of Nick Vannett and Juwan Johnson for work behind starter Adam Trautman. Hill has been involved as a passer (268 pass attempts), rusher (221 carries) and a receiver (47 targets) since joining the Saints in 2017, but his days as a quarterback appear to be numbered after he underwhelmed in place of Jameis Winston last season. Hill figures to see the occasional carry and some goal line work (he's scored at least five TDs from scrimmage each of the last three seasons), but he's an extreme long shot for enough work to find his way onto the fantasy radar. Leave him on waivers.

Arnold is back with the Jaguars after the team acquired him via trade early last season. The converted wide receiver played seven full games with Jacksonville and posted a 27-315-0 receiving line. His 17% target share was very generous, but the lack of scoring limited him to 21st in fantasy PPG. The arrival of TE-friendly coach Doug Pederson helps (career 31% TE target share in eight seasons), but Arnold may struggle for consistent usage with Evan Engram in the fold. Barring an Engram injury, Arnold is a long shot for his first top-20 fantasy campaign. The 27-year-old is not worth your attention in most formats.

Bell was selected by Cleveland in the third round of April's draft. He enters the pros after a productive three-year stint at Purdue in which he was heavily utilized as a short/intermediate target. Including a shortened 2020 campaign, Bell handled 26% of the targets and 36% of the air yards during his tenure. Impressively, he posted an 86-1,035-7 receiving line as an 18-year-old freshman in 2019. He's only 21, so there's plenty of room for development, though his combine showing raised several red flags, including a 4.65 40-yard dash (91 speed score). Amari Cooper is the only wide receiver locked into a starting role in Cleveland, so Bell could make some early-career noise if he overtakes Anthony Schwartz and/or Donovan Peoples-Jones. Monitor his progress throughout the summer.

Lock was sent to Seattle in the blockbuster Russell Wilson trade and the 2019 second-round pick will now compete to replace Wilson as the team's starting QB. Lock has appeared in 24 games in his career and they've resulted in 30 TDs (25 passing) and 20 INTs. Last season, Lock lost starting duties to Teddy Bridgewater and failed to impress during three late-season starts. Perhaps the change of scenery will ignite Lock's career, but his early-career resume suggests that's unlikely. Not much of a factor as a rusher, Lock is worth a bench spot in superflex formats only.

Denver hasn't had a dominant D/ST since 2016, but the unit overcame key injuries and the departure of Von Miller en route to a solid 14th-place finish in 2021. That included eight top-10 outings (tied for fifth). Despite playing in a tough AFC West, Denver allowed the eighth-fewest yards and third-fewest points last season, but struggled to create turnovers (21st) and sacks (18th). Offseason addition Randy Gregory should help with the latter and helps fill out a solid overall defense that is a little light on star power (Justin Simmons the obvious exception), but solid or better on all levels. This is a midrange fantasy unit with top-10 potential if second-year players Patrick Surtain II and Baron Browning make a leap.

Trubisky signed with the Steelers after holding the clipboard in Buffalo last season. The 2017 second-overall pick could open 2022 as the team's starter, but it's only a matter of time until first-round rookie Kenny Pickett takes over. Even if Trubisky does make some starts, there's not much to like. He took a step forward in his second pro season in 2018, but regressed in 2019 before being benched in 2020. He's yet to appear in a full regular season and his only top-25 fantasy campaign was a 15th-place finish in 2018. Trubisky adds a little with his legs, but not enough to move the needle. He's worth a look in superflex formats only.
